        "id": 266858,
        "name": "",
        "username": "TommySalami",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/tommysalami/{size}/51955_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-04-24T12:56:39.559Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Unfortunately, this is likely a server overhead limitation. Signal, being a nonprofit, likely doesn’t have deep enough pockets to support 4k video calls or even 1440. You gotta figure in all those video calls happening concurrently over its user base, and like Facetime, those calls probably drag on for a bit. It would definitely increase server overhead trying to handle call volume. Signal had like 40 million users in 2022 and if that number stayed static, if 2% of those users were making high quality video calls at any given time, that equates to 800,000 active calls being handled by Signal that needs to maintain equal resolution for all 800,000 calls of video and audio quality. Too much jitter or connection issues could be problematic.</p>\n<p>Further, and this a best guess, Signal also likely limits the call quality due higher bandwidth consuming a bunch of cell data. Many users have fixed data plans and not using WiFi for a video call can chew through monthly data limits in no time. Just a guess.</p>\n<p>Finally, and this is just my input, Signal likely keeps call quality lower for a more specific reason. Some Signal users are using signal in places where the internet has severe bandwidth limitation or is outright blocked and workarounds have to be implemented. High call bandwidth would make that difficult, though having a tiered quality system could help potentially.</p>",
