      {
        "id": 267605,
        "name": "",
        "username": "TommySalami",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/tommysalami/{size}/51955_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-05-07T11:56:35.996Z",
        "cooked": "<p>I mean, these other apps will lower the video quality based on bandwidth, ping etc. However, I have noticed that they work significantly better with limited bandwidth than Signal. I mean, a high quality call does use bandwidth, and that CAN tax Signal’s servers if they parties are calling through Signal’s servers, but honestly, having options related to priority, bandwidth etc. would be helpful. You can have the option of Signals servers, which kills call quality but provides security. On the flip side, not every call requires a video either and a VPN can mask your IP like routing through Signal’s servers, in a general way. Signal is a text service at heart, albeit a secure one, and I get the feeling that calling features weren’t really thought of as a highly/used requested feature.</p>\n<p>What would set Signal apart would be the option, as you mentioned, is P2P. Set up a Bluetooth mesh network between devices. The range would be severely limited, but at the end of the day, encrypted, secure, comms only over Bluetooth can significantly reduce a phone’s RF Emissions signature. Bluetooth can operate independent of WiFi, has a shorter range, has encryption itself, and is fully independent from the internet to function. Frequency hopping helps in a small way with jamming, but the limited range and power of Bluetooth itself can help overcome this and aid in positive message delivery.</p>\n<p>With anything there’s tradoffs and at some point, you gotta decrypt the message. I think that as more people use the service, and if they donate and aren’t freeloaders, then at some point, calling will improve even through Signal’s servers. Top quality VPN helps, but again, bandwidth and latency. For folks with a low latency, high bandwidth connection, calling, even with video, probably won’t ever be an issue for them. The issue is for the rest of the users that have one cell signal bar or those without high speed internet…so some of Signal’s most vulnerable users.</p>",
